NEW YORK = James Farmer,
director of the Congress of Rae
ial Equality announced general
plan for "a more meaningful
militancy' that would involve
CORE members more directly
in the political, economic and
social life of ghetto communities.


He announced the creation of
a new CORE executive position,
associated national director, to
be held by DR.. George A. Wiley,
founder of the CORE chapter in
Syracuse and an assistant pro-
lessor of chemistry at Syracuse
University.


The announcements we're made
during news conference at
CORE headquarters here. Far
mer said that the national CORE
was not abandoning its direct
action" policy of demonstrations
and civil disobedience.


"There will still be street de-
monstrations where they are
called for, but under our new
community action program we
hope to have block by block In
fluence and the ability to rally
entire communities to protest not
merely our own members, Far
mer said.


He said CORE would encourage
rent strikes, urban renewal pro-
iects, the formation of coopera-
tives by ghetto residents, and
participation in local political
activities.

director council of the NAACP

nounced that Clyde Harvey. Miss
issippi Civil Rights supporter.
has been freed from Jail.

sted and told he had been

90 days in Jail.
